File Compression
tar – Archives files:
Example: tar -czvf archive.tar.gz directory/.
zip – Compresses files:
Example: zip archive.zip file1 file2.
unzip – Extracts ZIP files.
gzip/gunzip – Compresses or decompresses files.
Process Management
ps – Displays running processes.
kill – Terminates a process:
Example: kill PID.
killall – Kills processes by name:
Example: killall firefox.
jobs – Lists background jobs.
fg/bg – Brings background jobs to the foreground or resumes them.
Searching and Filtering
grep – Searches text in files:
Example: grep "text" file.txt.
find – Locates files or directories:
Example: find /path -name "*.txt".
locate – Quickly searches for files (requires mlocate).
awk – Processes and analyzes text files.
sed – Edits text in a stream or file.
Package Management (Varies by Distribution)
For Debian/Ubuntu:
apt-get / apt – Installs, updates, or removes packages:
Example: sudo apt install package-name.
For Red Hat/CentOS:
yum / dnf – Installs, updates, or removes packages:
Example: sudo dnf install package-name.
For Arch Linux:
pacman – Installs, updates, or removes packages:
Example: sudo pacman -S package-name.
User Management
adduser / useradd – Adds a new user.
passwd – Changes a user’s password.
who – Shows logged-in users.
sudo – Executes commands with administrative privileges.
Other Useful Commands
history – Displays the history of executed commands.
alias – Creates shortcuts for commands:
Example: alias ll='ls -l'.
date – Displays or sets the system date and time.
env – Shows environment variables.
shutdown – Shuts down or restarts the system:
Example: shutdown -h now (shut down immediately).
find "$PWD" -name "filename" - find an absolute path
